Polymorphism in Java

â˜ Meaning of Polymorphism
Polymorphism is derived from two Greek words:
â†ªï¸Poly â†’ many
â†ªï¸Morphism â†’ forms
âºï¸ In Java, polymorphism means one interface (method name), many implementations (behaviors).
In simple terms:
â†ªï¸ The same method call can perform different actions depending on the object or parameters involved.

Types of Polymorphism in Java
| Type                      | When it happens    | Mechanism          |
| ------------------------- | ------------------ | ------------------ |
| Compile-time Polymorphism | During compilation | Method Overloading |
| Run-time Polymorphism     | During execution   | Method Overriding  |
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Compile-time Polymorphism (Method Overloading)
Definition
â†ªï¸ Method overloading occurs when multiple methods have the same name but different parameter lists in the same class.
The compiler decides which method to call based on arguments.
â€¢ Rules of Method Overloading
âœ” Same method name
âœ” Different parameter list (type, number, or order)
âœ˜ Cannot be achieved by return type alone
âœ” Can overload static and final methods
âœ” Happens within the same class

Example:-
class Solution{
int add(int a, int b){
return a+b; }

double div(double a, double b){
return a/b; }

public static void main(String [] args){
Solution S= new Solution();

System.out.println("Addition "+S.add(10,5);
System.out.println("Multiplication "+S.div(10,5);
 }
}

â˜… How Compiler Decides (Compile-time)
â–¶ Looks at method name
â–¶ Matches number of parameters
â–¶ Matches data types
â–¶ Selects best match
â–¶ This decision happens before program execution.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Run-time Polymorphism (Method Overriding)
Definition
â†ªï¸ Method overriding occurs when a child class provides its own implementation of a method already defined in the parent class.
The decision of which method to call is made at runtime, based on the object.

â€¢ Rules of Method Overriding
âœ” Same method name
âœ” Same parameter list
âœ” Must use inheritance
âœ” Access level cannot be reduced
âœ˜ final, static, and private methods cannot be overridden
âœ” Return type must be same or covariant

Example:-
class Parents{
void car(){
System.out.println("Car are start in every Morning");
}

class Child extends Parents{
  @Override
void car(){
System.out.println("Bike are not start in Night");
}

public static void main(String [] args){
Parents C= new Child();
c.car();
}
}

â˜… How JVM Decides (Run-time)
â–¶ JVM checks actual object type, not reference type
â–¶ Uses Dynamic Method Dispatch
â–¶ Method call resolved during execution

Differences: Overloading vs Overriding
| Feature            | Overloading                 | Overriding         |
| ------------------ | --------------------------- | ------------------ |
| Polymorphism type  | Compile-time                | Run-time           |
| Inheritance needed | No                          | Yes                |
| Method signature   | Same name, different params | Same name & params |
| Binding            | Static                      | Dynamic            |
| Performance        | Faster                      | Slightly slower    |

